[
    {
        "content": "<p>In dependent type theory with universes, each universe is typically taken to be a type in the empty context. Has anybody ever explored a notion of \"universe\" which allows one to have certain \"universes\" which only make sense in certain non-empty contexts?</p>\n<p>I'm not sure what an example might be -- I'm asking partly because I'm curious if anybody has ever found a motivation to study such a thing!</p>",
        "id": 306881418,
        "sender_full_name": "Tim Campion",
        "timestamp": 1667072599
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Here's an attempt at an example. Consider a dependent type theory for modal reasoning. Let's say that among the types available for you are certain \"types of possible worlds\". For simplicity, maybe there's just one type <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>⊣</mo><mi>W</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\dashv W</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⊣</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">W</span></span></span></span> whose terms are the elements of some Kripke frame or something. Then maybe  you could have, in the context of a possible world <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>w</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>W</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">w: W</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02691em;\">w</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">W</span></span></span></span>, a dependent universe <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>w</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>W</mi><mo>⊣</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">U</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>w</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">w : W \\dashv \\mathcal U(w)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02691em;\">w</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">W</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⊣</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.09931em;\">U</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02691em;\">w</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> where a term of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">U</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>w</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal U(w)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.09931em;\">U</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02691em;\">w</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> is some kind of type which only makes sense to talk about in the context of the possible world <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>w</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">w</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02691em;\">w</span></span></span></span>.... This doesn't sound so convincing so far -- it seems like right now <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">U</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal U</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.09931em;\">U</span></span></span></span> could be formalized as an ordinary universe which simply has different terms in the context of different possible worlds, as one would expect. To make it more interesting... what if the rules for universe formation can vary between the possible worlds? Like, maybe in the empty context there is only one universe, but in some possible worlds there is a \"successor\" operation on universes which spawns some possible-world-dependent hierarchy of universes....</p>",
        "id": 306881432,
        "sender_full_name": "Tim Campion",
        "timestamp": 1667072608
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Here's another attempted example. Think about algebraic geometry, and specifically about motivic homotopy theory. The <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\infty</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">∞</span></span></span></span>-category <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>H</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>S</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">H(S)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08125em;\">H</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> of motivic spaces over a base scheme <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>S</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">S</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span></span></span></span> is locally cartesian closed, but is typically not an <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\infty</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">∞</span></span></span></span>-topos -- descent fails. However, there <em>are</em> _some_ universes in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>H</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>S</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">H(S)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08125em;\">H</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>. These are various \"moduli stacks\" parameterizing different classes of motivic spaces. I'm not an expert, but I would guess that probably the question \"which classes of motivic spaces in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>H</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>S</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">H(S)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08125em;\">H</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> are parameterized by a moduli stack?\" (i.e. \"what universes exist in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>H</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>S</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">H(S)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08125em;\">H</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>?\") will have an answer which _depends_ on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>S</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">S</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span></span></span></span>. So you could maybe imagine a type theory where the types are roughly motivic spaces, and where the context can include a \"base scheme\" <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>S</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">S</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span></span></span></span> (or maybe more generally a \"base motivic space\"). Then depending on this contextual factor (which base scheme you're working over), the rules for universe formation might vary. So you might end up thinking in terms of \"universes\" which only make sense in certain contexts.</p>",
        "id": 306881868,
        "sender_full_name": "Tim Campion",
        "timestamp": 1667072958
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Anyway, whatever motivation one might have, I guess my questions are:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>\n<p>Is it clear what should be encompassed by a theory of \"dependent universes\"? </p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Has anybody written about a theory of \"dependent universes\"?</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Is there some good motivation to explore such a notion (whether along the lines of my attempted examples, or otherwise)?</p>\n</li>\n</ol>",
        "id": 306881993,
        "sender_full_name": "Tim Campion",
        "timestamp": 1667073063
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>[Obligatory joke about these being objects of study in some possible world]</p>",
        "id": 306882140,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1667073157
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The motivic spaces example certainly looks like compelling motivation to me, I'm sure someone can run with that. I would be (pleasantly!) surprised if dependent universes have already received attention, although I'm by no means the person who would know if that were the case.</p>",
        "id": 306882393,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1667073338
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I guess you could also do something like the following. Maybe your theory includes a type <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>T</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">T</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">T</span></span></span></span> of \"witnesses that the Grothendieck universe axiom holds\". In the context of some <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>t</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>T</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">t:T</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6151em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">t</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">T</span></span></span></span>, you can now form a whole bunch of new universes which you couldn't in the empty context (assuming that there's no closed term of type <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>T</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">T</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">T</span></span></span></span>). Maybe you could even find yourself mapping the territory of the set-theoretic multiverse with some framework like this...</p>",
        "id": 306882488,
        "sender_full_name": "Tim Campion",
        "timestamp": 1667073399
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>What about plain universe polymorphism?  <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>i</mi><mo>:</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">L</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">v</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">l</mi></mrow><mo>⊢</mo><msub><mi>U</mi><mi>i</mi></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">i : \\mathsf{Level} \\vdash U_i </annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6595em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">i</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\">Level</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⊢</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">U</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3117em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.109em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">i</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>.  Universe levels aren't always actually variables in a context, but I think in Agda there is actually a type of levels (which belongs to the $$\\omega$$th universe).</p>",
        "id": 306889346,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1667078831
    },
